'''Dexter Morriam Keezer''' (24 August 1895 – June 24, 1991) was a United States economist and served as president of [[Reed College]] from 1934–42.
==Biography== Dexter Merriam Keezer was born Aug. 24, 1895, in [[Acton, Massachusetts]].<ref name="nyt">{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1991/06/25/obituaries/dexter-m-keezer-is-dead-at-95-economist-gauged-us-outlook.html |title=Dexter M. Keezer Is Dead at 95; Economist Gauged U.S. Outlook |first=ALFONSO A. |last=NARVAEZ |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 25, 1991 |publisher=[[New York Times Company|NYTC]] |location=[[New York, NY|New York]] |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=11 October 2012}}</ref> He graduated from [[Amherst College]] in 1920, received an M.A. from [[Cornell University]] in 1923 and a PhD from the Brookings Graduate School of Economics and Government in 1925. He has taught at [[Cornell]], the [[University of Colorado]], the [[University of North Carolina]], and [[Dartmouth College]].
He served as president of [[Reed College]] from 1934-42.<ref>{{cite web|title=Presidents of Reed|url=http://www.reed.edu/president/reed_presidents/keezer.html|publisher=Reed College|accessdate=11 October 2012}}</ref> Reed founded the department of economics at [[McGraw-Hill]] after joining the company in 1945.<ref name="nyt"/>
Keezer died in 1991 in [[Orleans, Massachusetts]].<ref name="nyt"/>
